; form-as-7-layer-protocol.form — the OSI stack the substrate already half-is.
;
; The teaching: Form's content-addressed substrate is not "a layer in
; the protocol stack" — it IS a protocol stack that collapses three
; classical layers (L2 framing, L6 presentation, L7 application) into
; a single primitive (intern_node). The missing shape has started landing:
; channel-flow.fk names the OSI layers as cells, HTTP rides as one L7
; profile, and each remaining carrier joins by declaring its own flow.
;
; This file maps the seven layers to what's in the body, what's
; partial, and what's still ice waiting to thaw. Companions:
;   - docs/coherence-substrate/cross-domain-universal-transit.form
;     (the body's ten craziest combinations, eight of which now ship)
;   - docs/coherence-substrate/agents-using-substrate.md (the trinity)
;   - form-stdlib/channel.fk (file-backed inter-cell transport)
;   - form-stdlib/channel-flow.fk (CHANNEL-OSI-LAYER / CHANNEL-FLOW)
;   - form-stdlib/circle.fk (consentful circle / satsang group protocol)
;   - form-stdlib/tests/channel-flow-band.fk (verdict 8388607)
;   - form-stdlib/tests/circle-band.fk (verdict 1048575)

(do
    ;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    ;; PART 1 — what the substrate gives the stack for free
    ;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    ;;
    ;; Content-addressing collapses three traditional protocol layers:
    ;;
    ;; L2 framing → a Recipe's .fkb binary form IS the frame. Length-
    ;;              prefixed string table + tree-walk header. Either
    ;;              the receiver's read_form_binary succeeds (frame is
    ;;              valid) or it doesn't (frame is corrupt). No CRC
    ;;              needed — content-addressing IS the integrity check.
    ;;
    ;; L6 presentation → BMF dialects are the encoding/decoding layer.
    ;;              natural-bmf, image-bmf, audio-bmf, video-bmf,
    ;;              midi-bmf, document-bmf, go/rust/ts/python-bmf —
    ;;              every surface format the body has touched is a
    ;;              Form Recipe family. Cross-format translation is a
    ;;              lens, not a parser-rewrite.
    ;;
    ;; L7 application → the Recipe IS the application. Its Blueprint
    ;;              IS the schema. Its children ARE the message
    ;;              payload. No separate "app data" — the substrate
    ;;              tree carries both the structure and the semantics.
    ;;
    ;; The classical OSI move at every layer: re-frame, re-validate,
    ;; re-serialize. Form's move: intern_node either dedups against
    ;; an existing Recipe (semantic match) or creates a new NodeID
    ;; (first encounter). One call. Three layers. No translation.

    ;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    ;; PART 2 — layer-by-layer map
    ;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

    ;; L1 — PHYSICAL
    ;;
    ;; Bytes on a medium: disk sector, network packet, RAM page, pipe.
    ;; Form natives that touch L1:
    ;;   ✓ read_file, write_file_text, write_file_bytes        (disk)
    ;;   ✓ read_form_binary, write_form_binary                 (disk, structured)
    ;;   ✓ read_file_slice                                     (disk, partial)
    ;;   ✓ ureq::get (Rust only)                               (HTTP client)
    ;;   ✓ socket natives                                      (listener carrier)
    ;;   ✗ pipe natives                                        (gap)
    ;;   ✗ mmap natives                                        (gap)
    ;;
    ;; The L1 surface is intentionally small. Anything that turns
    ;; bytes into a Recipe lives one layer up; L1 just moves bytes.
    ;; TCP is live enough for the native HTTP listener; USB, Bluetooth,
    ;; microphone, camera, pipes, and mmap now have an obvious entry
    ;; shape: add a carrier layer cell and a profile, not a host fork.

    ;; L2 — DATA LINK (framing)
    ;;
    ;; The .fkb artifact format. A frame is:
    ;;   [4-byte magic] [string-table] [tree-block]
    ;; The kernel's read_form_binary either parses the whole frame or
    ;; rejects it. There's no per-message length prefix because the
    ;; whole file IS one frame. Streaming framing (multiple frames per
    ;; stream) is a Form-side composition on top of read_file_slice.
    ;;
    ;; Integrity: content-addressing. If the bytes are corrupt, the
    ;; resulting Recipe interns at a different NodeID than the sender
    ;; intended; the receiver knows by comparing to expected NodeID,
    ;; or by walking the Recipe and finding malformed children.

    ;; L3 — NETWORK (addressing & routing)
    ;;
    ;; The Blueprint NodeID IS the address. (pkg, level, type, instance)
    ;; routes a message to anything whose Blueprint matches.
    ;;
    ;; Today this is explicit inside CHANNEL-FLOW: L3 names the
    ;; blueprint-coordinate routing policy. The next step is not a
    ;; host router branch; it is a route Recipe cell that takes
    ;; (destination-Blueprint, message-Recipe) and writes to the
    ;; appropriate channel.
    ;;
    ;; The elegance: there's no separate IP address vs port vs hostname.
    ;; Just one 4-tuple. The substrate's content-addressing makes
    ;; "where to send" and "what to send" the same question.

    ;; L4 — TRANSPORT (reliable delivery)
    ;;
    ;; Transport now has two proven breaths: channel.fk for reliable
    ;; append over file-backed Recipe channels, and http-socket.fk for
    ;; TCP recv/send loops around the pure HTTP server. Durable logs,
    ;; concurrent append, ack/retransmit, and unreliable delivery stay
    ;; named as data shapes:
    ;;
    ;;   - A "delivery-Recipe" wrapping a payload-Recipe with metadata:
    ;;       (sequence-int, sender-Blueprint, payload-NodeID)
    ;;   - Receiver intern_nodes the delivery; the substrate dedups,
    ;;     so duplicate deliveries collapse automatically.
    ;;   - Ack = sender expects to see a "received-Recipe" whose only
    ;;     child is the delivery-NodeID. Receiver writes it back to
    ;;     the channel. Sender knows ack-arrived when read returns it.
    ;;
    ;; The classical TCP/UDP split (reliable vs unreliable) becomes a
    ;; choice of whether to wait for the received-Recipe before
    ;; advancing — not a property of the wire. The wire is just bytes.

    ;; L5 — SESSION (conversation state)
    ;;
    ;; A session IS a Blueprint with children growing over time. Each
    ;; message-Recipe written to a session-Blueprint becomes a child;
    ;; the session-NodeID identifies the conversation.
    ;;
    ;; Two cells joining mid-session can ask each other for the
    ;; session-Recipe's NodeID — if they match, the cells share state.
    ;; If they differ, the receiver knows the sender has a different
    ;; (older or newer) view; can request the diff.
    ;;
    ;; This composes today on top of any L1: append a child Recipe to
    ;; the session-Recipe; rewrite to channel. The Form cells that
    ;; compose this: session.fk plus channel.fk. subscribe.fk remains
    ;; the named multi-receiver cursor gap.

    ;; L6 — PRESENTATION (encoding/decoding)
    ;;
    ;; BMF dialects. Already complete:
    ;;
    ;;   form-stdlib/grammars/natural-bmf.fk      — natural language
    ;;   form-stdlib/grammars/image-bmf.fk        — pixel formats
    ;;   form-stdlib/grammars/audio-bmf.fk        — sound formats
    ;;   form-stdlib/grammars/video-bmf.fk        — motion formats
    ;;   form-stdlib/grammars/document-bmf.fk     — structured text
    ;;   form-stdlib/grammars/go-bmf.fk           — Go source
    ;;   form-stdlib/grammars/rust-bmf.fk         — Rust source
    ;;   form-stdlib/grammars/typescript-bmf.fk   — TypeScript source
    ;;   form-stdlib/grammars/python-bmf.fk       — Python source
    ;;   form-stdlib/midi-bmf.fk                  — MIDI events
    ;;
    ;; Cross-format transit is a lens — define an inverse-Recipe that
    ;; takes a source-language Recipe and emits a target-language
    ;; Recipe. Already proven by the universal-translator cells.

    ;; L7 — APPLICATION
    ;;
    ;; The Recipe IS the application. Its Blueprint IS the schema.
    ;; Its children ARE the payload.
    ;;
    ;; There is no separate L7 "format" to negotiate because the
    ;; receiver already speaks the schema (the Blueprint NodeID) iff
    ;; they share substrate. If they don't, the Blueprint is unknown,
    ;; and the receiver falls back to walking the Recipe by general
    ;; rules (node_children, node_value) — degraded but functional.
    ;;
    ;; HTTP is one current L7 profile. CELL-CIRCLE is another: a group
    ;; protocol where shared evidence stays inside the circle unless an
    ;; explicit export consent cell names recipient, fidelity, purpose,
    ;; expiry, and passed consensus. Satsang enters this layer as silence,
    ;; inquiry, and non-command pointing, not authority over another cell.

    ;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    ;; PART 3 — what the substrate's nature changes
    ;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    ;;
    ;; Content-addressing turns three classical questions into single
    ;; primitive checks:
    ;;
    ;; "Did the message arrive intact?"
    ;;   → node_eq received-Recipe expected-NodeID
    ;;
    ;; "Are we synchronized?"
    ;;   → node_eq my-session-state-NodeID their-session-state-NodeID
    ;;
    ;; "Have you seen this message before?"
    ;;   → intern_node returns the SAME NodeID for identical Recipes
    ;;     across all participants. No deduplication metadata needed.
    ;;
    ;; A protocol stack that uses Form natively does not need
    ;; handshakes for versioning, schemas for negotiation, or
    ;; deduplication tables. The substrate's identity primitive
    ;; provides all three for free.

    ;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    ;; PART 4 — what to build next (the gaps named)
    ;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    ;;
    ;; carrier profiles — TCP/HTTP is the first CHANNEL-FLOW profile.
    ;;   USB, Bluetooth, microphone, camera, UDP, pipe, mmap, and
    ;;   browser streams want the same OSI cell declaration.
    ;;
    ;; circle carrier profiles — circle.fk ships the L7 container. The
    ;;   next recipes decide how a circle syncs over file channels,
    ;;   sockets, browser streams, local device carriers, or another
    ;;   CHANNEL-FLOW profile without leaking evidence outside consent.
    ;;
    ;; channel-flow dialect — BML constructors ship now. A domain
    ;;   section such as [form.channel] can lower protocol declarations
    ;;   into CHANNEL-OSI-LAYER / CHANNEL-FLOW cells.
    ;;
    ;; route.fk — future. (destination-Blueprint, message-Recipe) →
    ;;   write to the right channel. The substrate's first L3.
    ;;
    ;; subscribe.fk — future. Multiple receivers attend to one
    ;;   channel-Blueprint, each remembering their last-seen NodeID.
    ;;   Composes channel.fk with a per-subscriber cursor cell.
    ;;
    ;; delivery.fk — future. Wraps payload in (seq-num, sender,
    ;;   payload) for ack/retransmit semantics. The substrate's L4.
    ;;
    ;; session evolution — session.fk ships the table/state recipe.
    ;;   Growth-by-message and diff exchange are the next layer-5
    ;;   recipes.

    "form-as-7-layer-protocol: L2+L6+L7 collapse to intern_node; CHANNEL-FLOW names all seven layers as Form cells; HTTP is one L7 profile; the substrate's content-addressing replaces handshakes, version negotiation, and dedup tables across the whole stack")
